<p>In 1950, <a href="/wiki/Secretary_of_Defense" class="mw-redirect" title="Secretary of Defense">Secretary of Defense</a> <a href="/wiki/George_C._Marshall" class="mw-redirect" title="George C. Marshall">George C. Marshall</a> and <a href="/wiki/Secretary_of_the_Navy" class="mw-redirect" title="Secretary of the Navy">Secretary of the Navy</a> <a href="/wiki/Francis_P._Matthews" title="Francis P. Matthews">Francis P. Matthews</a> called on the USO which was disbanded by 1947 to provide support for U.S. servicemen.<sup id="cite_ref-pmedwards123124_389-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pmedwards123124-389">[386]</a></sup> By the end of the war, more than 113,000 USO volunteers from the U.S. were working at home front and abroad.<sup id="cite_ref-pmedwards123124_389-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pmedwards123124-389">[386]</a></sup> Many stars came to Korea to give their performances.<sup id="cite_ref-pmedwards123124_389-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-pmedwards123124-389">[386]</a></sup> Throughout the Korean War, <a href="/wiki/Prostitutes_in_South_Korea_for_the_U.S._military" title="Prostitutes in South Korea for the U.S. military">UN Comfort Stations</a> were operated by South Korean officials for UN soldiers.<sup id="cite_ref-H.C3.B6hn5152_390-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-H.C3.B6hn5152-390">[387]</a></sup></p>